    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a8e6c396_4c28e426",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream.h",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 46,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-20T04:12:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e In the test, I test the compressed data is less or larger than the buffer. It return the length of the buffer, and can\u0027t be static, right?\n\nHmm. The old arraysize() would have worked and ARRAYSIZE_UNSAFE would work, but it won’t work with std::size() or base::size(), which is based on std::size().\n\nBut like I said, I don’t think you need this at all. It’s generally considered OK for a test to “know” things like the internal buffer size of the class it’s testing so that it can choose sizes equal to or near, and sizes definitely much smaller and definitely much larger.\n\nI don’t like complicating main implementations solely for the benefit of the tests.",
      "parentUuid": "4476fcdf_f0f65542",
      "revId": "fe231a5ef7e78ab56dcf18bb10a32d6b8f2e3a61",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
